<br>
We did execution last night with an AoE group, and completely destroyed it. The mobs died so quickly and we had so long between each wave that I thought we'd broken it somehow as the gap between waves was so long. If you've been struggling to get through with pick up groups (even skilled ones) then definitely try it, we won first attempt with AoE. Here's the technique we used just in case you are a little worried about the details (I was before we did it).<br>
<br>
----------------------<br>
AoE Trial of Execution<br>
----------------------<br>
<br>
Our group makeup was :<br>
<br>
3 wiz (60, 60, 65), 1 ench (62), 1 war (61), 1 cler (62)<br>
<br>
Everyone was reasonably geared, but certainly not VT level stuff, I imagine that a lower level of equip would be fine although take a reasonable warrior as he has to tank the executioner at the end.<br>
<br>
It should also be possible to do it with 2 wizards with decent mana pool - with 3 we all had oodles of mana left by the end. Others have had success with 2 ench, but frankly its totally unnecessary, no one got below 80% hp at any point, but if you need to get 2 ench through its an option.<br>
<br>
Spell line up: just load both jylls (ice+fire) and some nukes for finishing the boss. Fwiw I found Elnericks was resisted a bit too much in this event, so probably sunstrike is the best choice for him (or whatever pop spells you have).<br>
<br>
All mobs appart from the rocks are stunnable. We certainly took very little damage. The mini-bosses may be immune too, but even with 4 unstunables, you'd probably get away with it if you have 3 wizzies in decent gear.<br>
<br>
Technique is similar to how a typical group would do the trial. Everyone except the warrior stand in the right corner (on wall furthest away from stage). Warrior stands in middle and gets aggro when they spawn so mobs end up huddled on him. Everyone else then runs into centre and does standard aoe massacre. Mobs then die in about 15-20 secs. Its funny after the first mob dies watching the executioner not even get a couple of steps towards the stage each time - at least it was to me having failed in a normal melee group a few times...<br>
<br>
Tell the warrior to attack and taunt the rocks as they aren't stunnable and if he can get aggro for a bit, it will help a tad. In the end it probably doesn't matter though as aggro is likely to bounce amongst the wizards, not the crucial chanter. DPS of the mobs in this trial is actually pretty low, so don't sweat about the named/rocks.<br>
<br>
After a wave dies, everyone but the warrior back in the corner. Make sure the cleric keeps group at full health between spawns, you have tonnes of time to med, heal and lotto on any drops.<br>
<br>
On the 4th wave, remember that the executioner will appear on the stage as the last mob dies. The warrior needs to start moving to the stage as soon as the last mob dies (or just before), whilst everyone else should move a little away. Let the warrior get aggro and slow/debuff the executioner. He rampages for 700ish so try not to get aggro. This part is actually pretty easy though as you should have a of mana left (&gt;60% in my case IIRC), as long as cleric doesn't get aggro from healing the warrior. Make sure they have DA memmed and ready just in case.<br>
<br>
Currently there is a bug on slowing the executioner, and the ench needs to use a lower level spell. This should be fixed soon, but I can't remember the name of the slow ours used. Possibly tepid deeds...<br>
<br>
The hardest part of the whole thing was persuading the enchanter that it could be done.<br>
<br>
-------------------<br>
